AI-Related Testing in Jumio


At Jumio, I led quality strategy and automation for an AI-based Document Verification platform used for KYC, onboarding, and Proof of Address across 14 countries, 8 languages, and 24 document types.

Unlike traditional systems, testing AI pipelines requires validating probabilistic outputs, OCR quality, NLP extraction accuracy, PII masking correctness, model drift, bias, and regulatory compliance.

I built a multi-layered testing framework covering:
* Data validation
* Model accuracy validation
* Pipeline reliability
* Workflow orchestration correctness
* Production monitoring & drift detection
I automated model evaluation using golden datasets, confidence-threshold validation, regression benchmarking, and synthetic document generation, and integrated these into CI/CD.
This reduced false positives to ~1%, stabilized model releases, and enabled safe rollout across multilingual and multi-format document types at scale.

At Jumio-style platforms, I worked on:
* OCR models (text extraction)
* Document classification models (passport, DL, ID card)
* Forgery/tamper detection models
* Face match/liveness models


What Makes AI Testing Different?

Input → Output == Expected


AI testing checks:

Input → Output ∈ Probability Distribution → Acceptable Confidence Range

So instead of exact correctness, you test:
* Accuracy thresholds
* Precision / Recall
* Confidence scores
* Drift
* Bias
* Robustness to noise
Interviewers want to hear this mindset shift.

